1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:01,440
Hi everyone.

2
00:00:02,000 --> 00:00:11,940
In this video we'll examine the power part of a full-bridge scheme for swinging a Tesla transformer inductor in resonance mode.

3
00:00:12,960 --> 00:00:18,540
We start with the elements that control the transformer for us.

4
00:00:19,020 --> 00:00:21,980
These are two TC4420 drivers.

5
00:00:22,340 --> 00:00:28,760
These drivers can work up to 6 A in pulse, so they suit us well.

6
00:00:30,000 --> 00:00:34,600
And they'll further control the gates not only of IRF840 transistors.

7
00:00:35,380 --> 00:00:55,160
Here you can put instead of these transistors any other FET or IGBT transistors with voltage no less than 600 V — well, and corresponding amperages, depending on what tasks you want to pursue further.

8
00:00:55,160 --> 00:01:12,080
Also if you'll change transistors to others, then you'll only need to pick the limiting resistances that go to the side of the FET transistor gate.

9
00:01:13,060 --> 00:01:21,300
The bigger the gate capacitance of the transistor chosen by you, the smaller this resistance.

10
00:01:21,300 --> 00:01:31,740
Accordingly, the load on these two drivers will be larger and the control system will ultimately have larger consumption.

11
00:01:32,100 --> 00:01:42,800
The transformer itself is made on ferrite with permeability 2500 in the form of a pot core from two halves.

12
00:01:43,560 --> 00:01:45,400
Dimensions are shown in the picture.

13
00:01:45,400 --> 00:01:49,940
This is how the core looks in reality.

14
00:01:50,300 --> 00:02:04,440
Two halves of small dimensions that after laying wire inside are fixed with the help of a thread connection, tightening directly on the board.

15
00:02:06,300 --> 00:02:14,540
Instead of this core, if you don't find such, you can use a ferrite ring with the same permeability.

16
00:02:16,220 --> 00:02:25,800
The primary winding is 12.5 turns for us, and 4 secondary windings of 11.5 turns each.

17
00:02:27,320 --> 00:02:40,720
The wire by length that went into this winding — we have 5 windings, ultimately 60 cm of wire went, counting these leads.

18
00:02:41,640 --> 00:02:49,800
How the wire is wound — gathered into a bundle of 5 parallel wires and wound simultaneously.

19
00:02:50,380 --> 00:02:58,540
After winding, choose one of the conductors and do one more additional turn.

20
00:02:59,220 --> 00:03:05,660
That is, this will further be our primary winding that has 12.5 turns.

21
00:03:07,120 --> 00:03:15,160
The primary winding is swung by our drivers through the isolation transformer.

22
00:03:15,380 --> 00:03:18,960
Its capacity is 1.5 µF at 250 volts.

23
00:03:19,000 --> 00:03:26,840
I marked it as a film capacitor of corresponding dimensions in iron.

24
00:03:27,020 --> 00:03:28,980
You'll see it further too.

25
00:03:28,980 --> 00:03:34,780
At the driver outputs are two diodes with corresponding inclusion.

26
00:03:35,700 --> 00:03:52,340
According to the driver's power, they're called in the scheme like this to smooth spikes that form during work under load of the primary winding of the pulse transformer.

27
00:03:52,340 --> 00:03:59,460
The pulses that are supplied to control the drivers have a 180-degree shift.

28
00:04:00,420 --> 00:04:04,180
And through the winding they're directed counter to each other.

29
00:04:04,300 --> 00:04:14,020
So on the primary and secondary winding we'll see a bipolar signal.

30
00:04:15,440 --> 00:04:26,400
Controlling such a signal through the pulse transformer, we provide the corresponding operation of the bridge scheme of the inverter.

31
00:04:27,140 --> 00:04:31,200
It turns out our transistors work diagonally in pairs.

32
00:04:32,680 --> 00:04:38,260
On the scheme it's visible that I marked the start of windings with dots.

33
00:04:39,080 --> 00:04:42,160
During assembly watch this moment.

34
00:04:42,280 --> 00:04:47,180
It's very important that your transistors specifically work in pairs diagonally.

35
00:04:47,320 --> 00:04:48,480
For example, look.

36
00:04:49,000 --> 00:04:55,900
The dot at the start of the winding goes to the gate of one of the keys.

37
00:04:57,080 --> 00:05:09,100
Accordingly, the gate of the second key diagonally — if you walk through the scheme — is also connected through a current-limiting resistor to the start of the winding.

38
00:05:09,740 --> 00:05:15,260
The other pair of these transistor gates is connected to the ends of the windings.

39
00:05:17,060 --> 00:05:19,820
Track this moment.

40
00:05:20,680 --> 00:05:26,100
The IRF840 transistor is made in a case for through-hole mounting.

41
00:05:26,760 --> 00:05:28,020
Has three leads.

42
00:05:28,020 --> 00:05:32,000
The leads are counted from left to right accordingly.

43
00:05:32,120 --> 00:05:34,220
This will be the first lead, second, and third.

44
00:05:34,600 --> 00:05:37,360
The first lead on the scheme is the gate.

45
00:05:37,900 --> 00:05:38,920
This dot here.

46
00:05:39,520 --> 00:05:41,300
The second lead is the drain.

47
00:05:42,000 --> 00:05:44,280
This dot here at the transistor.

48
00:05:44,740 --> 00:05:46,420
And the third lead is the source.

49
00:05:46,580 --> 00:05:50,800
Accordingly, this lead on the scheme.

50
00:05:51,800 --> 00:05:57,540
Parallel to the transistor is a MUR460 diode.

51
00:05:59,700 --> 00:06:02,940
It's made in a standard cylindrical case.

52
00:06:04,280 --> 00:06:12,820
It serves to short out OIDS spikes during inverter work on inductive load.

53
00:06:13,820 --> 00:06:25,480
Under other transistors, if you use more powerful ones, I recommend installing MUR860 diodes already in such a case.

54
00:06:25,640 --> 00:06:30,040
They're 8-amp and require installation on a heat sink.

55
00:06:30,220 --> 00:06:35,940
That is, installed on the same heat sink where the power key itself is located.

56
00:06:36,360 --> 00:06:38,240
In immediate proximity to it.

57
00:06:38,840 --> 00:06:45,260
These elements, zeners connected counter at 15 volts.

58
00:06:47,380 --> 00:06:50,600
Discharge resistance 1.2 kOhm.

59
00:06:50,820 --> 00:06:58,560
And current-limiting resistance installed on the board in immediate proximity to the gate of the FET key.

60
00:06:58,780 --> 00:07:06,100
The 1.2 kOhm resistor serves to discharge the gate capacitance of the FET key.

61
00:07:06,100 --> 00:07:18,260
Counter-connected zeners serve to cut spikes that form during pulse commutation of the isolation control transformer.

62
00:07:18,780 --> 00:07:26,060
Power to the power part of the bridge is supplied at these points, marked 1, 2.

63
00:07:26,060 --> 00:07:35,440
And here a smoothing accumulator electrolytic capacitor of 470 µF at 450 V is also connected.

64
00:07:36,100 --> 00:07:41,600
The maximum voltage I recommend supplying at these points is up to 400 V.

65
00:07:42,920 --> 00:07:54,500
This system works successfully with 150 W consumption — that's on the order of 300 V, half an amp by DC.

66
00:07:55,020 --> 00:08:00,520
The system doesn't overheat, the heat sink temperature is in the area of 45 degrees.

67
00:08:00,520 --> 00:08:09,640
On the scheme it's visible that I installed a capacitor in series with the Tesla transformer inductor.

68
00:08:10,440 --> 00:08:14,700
It's written that it needs to be picked in resonance.

69
00:08:15,160 --> 00:08:22,640
I picked this oscillating circuit according to the carrier frequency of the main Tesla transformer.

70
00:08:22,640 --> 00:08:27,980
You can also use this converter without this capacitor.

71
00:08:28,540 --> 00:08:35,280
Then the Tesla transformer swinging will be done specifically with such bipolar pulses.

72
00:08:36,780 --> 00:08:45,460
If a capacitor is used here in the scheme, we can examine the inductor connection.

73
00:08:46,460 --> 00:08:53,140
Here to the capacitor the inductor connects with its upper point.

74
00:08:53,960 --> 00:08:59,180
Here, to this transistor pair, the inductor connects with the lower point.

75
00:08:59,740 --> 00:09:12,880
The upper inductor point, if it's wound cylindrically around the Tesla transformer, for you will be the point directed toward the hot end of the Tesla transformer.

76
00:09:12,880 --> 00:09:15,360
And the lower point, accordingly, toward the cold end.

77
00:09:17,820 --> 00:09:31,100
The compatibility of this scheme is fully compatible with the previous half-bridge converter scheme I gave earlier.

78
00:09:32,100 --> 00:09:35,920
How to connect it instead of this power part?

79
00:09:36,920 --> 00:09:51,180
These TC4420 driver inputs are connected through a 16 Ohm resistor — accordingly, these points after the TC4093 chip.

80
00:09:51,840 --> 00:09:54,180
Pin 11 and pin 10.

81
00:09:55,040 --> 00:10:05,100
Power is also done from a DC-DC converter 12 to 400 V, or a lab block, whoever has what.

82
00:10:05,920 --> 00:10:09,820
And this is a separate DC-DC converter, also the same as on this scheme.

83
00:10:09,880 --> 00:10:12,860
This is the power for the logic part.

84
00:10:13,660 --> 00:10:23,700
And these 16 V come to power the drivers that swing the primary winding of the pulse transformer.

85
00:10:24,920 --> 00:10:28,160
Overall the scheme is quite simple, reliable.

86
00:10:28,720 --> 00:10:37,800
It mainly excluded the problem with the IR2110 and IR2113 driver.

87
00:10:38,780 --> 00:10:49,660
The driver temperature needs to be watched very clearly in that scheme, since the whole scheme would fail from overheating.

88
00:10:50,820 --> 00:11:00,600
People had such moments, so it was decided to develop one more scheme that's free of these shortcomings.

89
00:11:02,000 --> 00:11:15,400
The half-bridge scheme has the moment that it divides supply voltage in half, and the full bridge scheme doesn't suffer from such a shortcoming.

90
00:11:15,620 --> 00:11:24,360
That is, all the voltage applied at these points is commutated onto the primary winding of the Tesla transformer.

91
00:11:24,960 --> 00:11:32,680
If this scheme isn't connected to a Tesla transformer, you can successfully use it for other purposes.

92
00:11:32,920 --> 00:11:40,780
For example, get rid of this capacitor, put a corresponding inductor here and make some kind of converter.

93
00:11:42,320 --> 00:11:50,800
That is, you can successfully supply rectified mains voltage here and create step-down or step-up converters.

94
00:11:52,340 --> 00:11:54,020
Before you is the device board.

95
00:11:54,020 --> 00:12:02,500
You see the drivers, control transformer, and film capacitor.

96
00:12:03,600 --> 00:12:09,040
All gate components are located directly on the transistor leads.

97
00:12:09,220 --> 00:12:13,240
The transistors themselves are located on the heat sink under the board.

98
00:12:13,900 --> 00:12:23,620
The power transistor components are also located in the form of surface mount on the transistor legs.

99
00:12:24,020 --> 00:12:37,140
And these brought-out points are the places where the Tesla transformer inductor or any other primary winding of a power converter will be connected further.

100
00:12:38,500 --> 00:12:41,460
As you see, the board is quite simple.

101
00:12:42,700 --> 00:12:53,760
The main difficulty here is the moment that the leads of the control transformer need to be connected correctly.

102
00:12:54,140 --> 00:13:01,760
Once again I'll remind — they're connected diagonally according to the control scheme.

103
00:13:02,300 --> 00:13:04,400
This is how the BRIDGE power module looks.

104
00:13:05,060 --> 00:13:07,340
Four IRF840 transistors.

105
00:13:07,340 --> 00:13:18,020
Parallel to each transistor at its drain and source outputs is a MUR460 diode.

106
00:13:27,920 --> 00:13:33,480
Here I additionally put sleeves protecting the leads.

107
00:13:38,050 --> 00:13:43,650
Now you can see how the windings are laid inside the control transformer.

108
00:13:43,650 --> 00:13:49,470
As you see, they take up all the volume inside the pot core.

109
00:13:50,330 --> 00:14:01,010
To lay five conductors in this core, I chose wire with outer diameter by insulation of 0.7 mm.

110
00:14:01,830 --> 00:14:03,030
Insulation is fluoroplastic.

111
00:14:03,490 --> 00:14:07,430
These conductors are made qualitatively from pure copper.

112
00:14:07,710 --> 00:14:15,690
Furthermore, fluoroplastic insulation has excellent properties that prevent breakdown of high-voltage voltage.

113
00:14:16,310 --> 00:14:28,920
This is what we need, since large supply voltage potentials are applied to this inverter in our build.

114
00:14:29,890 --> 00:14:38,490
And if you use low-quality conductors, we risk getting a short circuit inside the control transformer.

115
00:14:39,250 --> 00:14:43,950
On this all the subtleties with this scheme are exhausted.

116
00:14:44,750 --> 00:14:50,770
Good mood to everyone, all the best, and excellent experiments.
